# 8. Comparison with Alternative Approaches

## MLIR Progressive Lowering vs LLVM Single IR

| Feature                      | LLVM IR   | MLIR            |
| ---------------------------- | --------- | --------------- |
| Multiple Abstraction Levels  | No        | Yes             |
| Custom Dialects              | Limited   | Fully Supported |
| Tensor Representation        | Low Level | Native Support  |
| Progressive Lowering         | No        | Yes             |
| Domain Specific Optimization | Difficult | Easy            |
| Extensibility                | Moderate  | High            |

Observation:

MLIR preserves tensor semantics throughout the compilation pipeline, enabling more effective optimization and easier implementation of domain-specific transformations.

---

# 9. Performance Observation

The lowering pass executes in a single traversal of the IR.

Observed characteristics:

* Low memory overhead
* Fast pattern matching
* Efficient type conversion
* Scalable to larger tensor programs

Since the project focuses on correctness and transformation rather than runtime optimization, functional correctness was prioritized over execution speed.

